sentence: Stocks finished little changed on Tuesday after big gains fueled by upbeat quarterly results from retailers Walmart ( WMT ), Home Depot ( HD ) and the TJX Companies ( TJX ), as well as quiet inflation data, turned into afternoon profit-taking.
Consumer and health care stocks earlier paced today's market, while another retreat for crude oil below $41 per barrel pressured shares of energy companies, also limiting today's advance.

All three of the major market gauges were recording strong gains mid-way through today's session, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average rising as much as 117 points with big gains for component companies Walmart and Home Depot before stalling out just before 17,600.
The S&P 500 turned lower earlier this afternoon and tried several times to climb back to positive ground only to finish virtually unchanged.
The Nasdaq Composite index followed a similar path throughout much of the day only to scratch out the smallest of gains.

Health care and consumer discretionary stocks were the only industry sectors in the S&P 500 to close above the break-even marks, with shares of utility companies joining energy stocks to lose over 1% in value today.

Tuesday's economic calendar included an as-expected 0.2% increase in the nominal and core consumer price indices, neither of which will be likely viewed as ammunition for the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates next month.

Also today, October industrial production contracted 0.2%, matching a similar decline during the prior month according to the Federal Reserve, while capacity utilization fell to 77.5% from September's upwardly revised 77.7% rate.
Wall Street was expecting industrial production to increase 0.1% and capacity utilization to remain unchanged at 77.5%.
Crude oil for December delivery settled $1.07 lower at $40.67 per barrel while December natural gas futures fell a penny to $2.37 per 1 million BTU.
December gold dropped $15 to finish at $1,068.60 per ounce while December copper slipped 1 cent to $2.10 per pound.

Here's where the U.S. markets stood at the end-of-day:

(+) NUAN, Fiscal Q4 net income of $0.41 per share tops analyst call expecting $0.35 per share profit.
Revenue edges 0.35% higher to $504.1 mln, narrowly missing $507.84 consensus.
(+) MARA, Non-GAAP net loss of $0.01 per share reverses $0.40 per share profit during year-ago period but easily beats Street view expecting $0.28 per share loss.
Revenue declines 52.3% year over year to $6.4 mln, topping the $4.8 mln consensus.

(+) SMMT, Extends cooperation pact with Oxford University through November 2019, to support development of utrophin modulators to treat Duchenne muscular dystrophy, a muscle-wasting disease mostly affecting young males.
(-) SUNE, Third Point Capital liquidates entire 12.4 mln-share stake during Q3 while Greenlight Capital trims ownership interest by roughly 25% to 18.2 mln shares.
(-) FSAM, Reschedules filing its Form 10-Q quarterly report with SEC, saying it expects to file its Q3 financial results by next Monday, Nov. 23.
(-) OSIR, Falls to 32-month low on Tuesday after stock was reduced to Sell from Hold with an $8 price target at Brean Capital.
